  • Regents, Kansas Board of (1925- )
    • The State Board of Administration was created March 20, 1913, for the management and control of the following State educational institutions: the University of Kansas, the Kansas State Normal Schools, the Kansas State Agricultural College, the Kansas School for the Deaf, at Olathe, and Kansas School for Blind, at Kansas City,' Kansas. These institutions were previously controlled by Boards of Regents. In 1917 the Legislature extended the functions of the Board to include all the educational, benevolent, and penal institutions, and required the Board to appoint a Business Manager. The charitable institutions were previously under the Board of Trustees of State Charitable Institutions, 1877-1902/04, and the Board of Control of State Charitable Institutions, 1904/06-1914/16, and the penal institutions under control of a Board of Corrections. In 1925 the control of the five major educational institutions, formerly under the Board of Administration was transferred to a newly created State Board of Regents. After further reorganization in 1939, the Board retained jurisdiction only over the penal institutions (Penitentiary, State Industrial Farm for Women, State Industrial Reformatory) and the Parole Board. The Charitable and Correctional Institutions were transferred to the newly created Department of Social Welfare, the two Negro schools and the institutions for the deaf, and the blind, were transferred to the reorganized State Board of Regents. The Business Manager works with the State Board of Regents, the State Department of Social Welware, and the Board of Administration. (Laws, 1939, ch. 285, p. 541.) The State Board of Administration was repealed July 1, 1953, and its duties, powers, jurisdiction transferred to the newly created Board of Penal Institutions. (Laws, 1953, ch. 375, sec. 56.)
      [From: Bibliography of the Official Publications of Kansas, 1854-1958. Bessie E. Wilder. Lawrence: Governmental Research Center, University of Kansas. 1965).
